  Aggregation with grouping works by combining related values from different levels of a hierarchy. For example, a hierarchy might be represented by a single relation city (ID, city, state, country, region), or by multiple relations, each mapping values in one level of the hierarchy to values at the next level. We assume here that cities have unique identifiers, stored in the attribute ID, to avoid confusing two cities with the same name, for example, the Springfield in Missouri and the Springfield in Illinois.
  
  For operations such as sum, count, and average, we can assume that all aggregation values are distinct. For min and max, the number of distinct values can be estimated as the minimum of V(A, r) and V(G, r), where G denotes grouping attributes. We omit details of estimating distinct values for other operations.
  
  On the other hand, relational aggregation and reduce operations may be unable to produce any output until the entire stream is consumed. To support such operations, Flinders supports window operations that break the stream into windows; aggregation is computed within each window and output once the window is complete. Note that the output is treated as a stream, where tuples have a timestamp based on the end of the window.
  ----------------------------------------------------------

