  SQL provides strong isolation guarantees by default. This means that transactions are treated as if they were isolated from each other, even if they are running concurrently. The isolation level determines the level of isolation provided by the database system. The default isolation level is typically set to "Repeatable Read," which ensures that a transaction sees the same data as another transaction at the start of the transaction. This helps to prevent race conditions and other issues that can arise from concurrent transactions. The isolation level can be changed by the user or the database system administrator.
  ----------------------------------------------------------

